The city of Astana was handpicked in the 1990s by President Nursultan Nazarbayev to be the new capital of Kazakhstan. Risen from a forsaken landscape and post-Soviet rubble, in just 25 years the place has become a futuristic city dominated by avant-garde architecture.
Nicknamed the grain elevator, the semicircular KazMunayGas Building houses the state-owned energy companies and like many buildings on Astana’s Left Bank goes through a kaleidoscopic color change every night.
