Portrait of Friedensreich Hundertwasser. As a young photographer I spent a couple of weeks with the world renowned Austrian artist at his huge, rugged and remote property in the native forest located in the Bay of Islands, an area on the northeast coast of New Zealand.

Friedensreich Regentag Dunkelbunt Hundertwasser (1928-2000), born Friedrich Stowasser, was a world renowned eccentric artist, architect and environmentalist. Concerned early on about the environment, he designed houses with grass roofs, undulating floors, and onion-shaped domes. In his art and architecture he used bright colors and organic forms, was fascinated by spirals, and considered straight lines as ‘immoral and godless’. See the image I posted last month of him taking a bath in his makeshift tub in the native forest of New Zealand

